Parliament has not ratified the amendment for the release of Tymosenko
The Ukrainian parliament, in the context of an amendment to criminal law, refused the draft annulment of the paragraph relating to the indictment of Julia Tymosenko, the leader of the opposition.
The MPs refused in second reading the proposed amendment to reduce the penalties for economic offences, which could have opened the doors of freedom for the former Prime Minister currently imprisoned.
Tymosenko was sentenced in October to 7 years in prison for having concluded a previously disadvantaged agreement with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The judgment is not final and the court is due on the appeal of the convicted person in December.
Tymosenko qualifies the judgment of political revenge of the regime and has provoked a process of suspicions of bias of the court to the west as well.
The draft annulment of paragraph 365 of the criminal law, on the basis of which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was signed by 147 Members.
It would have taken 226 votes to approve it.
