How travel prices have changed since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time were offering trips especially in the countries of the socialist bloc, as trips to the west were very limited.
Czech tourists traveled for holidays in East Germany, Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A great exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when he was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia and then the regime began to have a western inclination and travel to Yugoslavia were very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for the citizens of the socialist bloc (also for the Czechoslovaks) to travel individually even within the framework of the socialist countries.
If the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, in Poland or in the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter or the individual trip was not allowed.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West, however, it was necessary to queue all night with a sleeping bag or have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
And even after that it was not yet won.
The agreement for currencies that was the condition to travel to the west was denied to people "politically incorrect" who could not travel at all.
However, the Czechoslovak currency was not interchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial resources without the currency agreement (Western currency) to travel to the west.
The Czechs spent most of their vacations in the country where there were therefore many country houses and cottages that the Czechs bought and this habit lasts until now.
Czech travel has since experienced a great revolution in 1989.
Although until 1989 the holiday in East Germany and Bulgaria were at most, Czechs spent last year abroad 4 million vacation days in countries around the world.
The great paradox we are not aware of today is that the most popular country is Croatia where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because part of Yugoslavia of the time.
The removal of visas in the last 90s in neighbouring western countries caused a huge wave of short-term visits especially in Austria in Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not for a long time travel by plane to the west that everyone wanted to see at least one moment.
For example, in Paris travel organizations made Czechs sleep in tents in parks because our incomes did not allow us to pay for the hotel or a pension.
The typical feature of a Czech trip was at this time to take with itself its own canned food, sausage, etc... to save.
Another important moment was also the exchangeability of the Czech crown which enabled our tourists finally after decades of freely buying Western currency.
Our standard of living and the average wage have increased what has caused another important time around 1997.
Thanks to an increasing travel demand, travel agencies have begun since 1997 to prepare tours with air charter links that thanks to contracts have greatly reduced costs compared to what was before.
In the late 1990s, Czechs had visa-free connections with virtually most developed countries around the world except the EU which later facilitated our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when the first air charter was prepared to an exotic country, Thailand, from the Czech Republic.
Since this year as every year, direct air charters have taken Czech tourists to faraway hot countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
It is more than 100000 Czechs who visit exotic countries each year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolution development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the EU abolished visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to settle completely in the group of developed countries.
In 2008, also the Czechs for the first time in history spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50, 3%) and for the first time in history spent more than 15,000 crowns per person for vacation abroad including the attached charges.
