Facebook is full of so many personal information, says Jamie Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the site's advertising tool to find the people they are looking for with scientific accuracy - the way marketers have been doing it for years.
The Jamie Bartlett team discovered that half a million members are fans of far-right groups in Europe. It targeted them with announcements, but instead of linking them to a new group or product, the announcements invited users to respond to an inquiry. Questions related to their level of education, their attitudes to violence and their optimism about their own future.
By contacting these people through Facebook, Jamie Bartlett and his colleagues were able to question 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - without leaving the office.
"It's a new way to do research," says Jamie Bartlett.
Some results are not at all surprising: the online supporters of the right-wing groups are rather men, young and against immigration.
But surprisingly, "those who associate online and offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who remain behind their computer screen."
DEMOS' study is just one example of how Facebook became the new indispensable tool in the hands of scientists.
Thinking groups, medical researchers and polytologists use the site to study all the topics that affect health issues such as social trends, thanks to "I like", publications on walls and updates of statutes.
With more than 800 million active users adding on average three content per day, the "data supernova" generates an explosion in research, increasing the number of research works whose site name appears in the title of almost 800% over the last five years.
For some researchers, the advantage of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you could not approach on the street.
"Before, when you tried to investigate the people of the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You were supposed to go to the party, but they would never have allowed you to come in," says Jamie Bartlett.
"Facebook avoids all this - you have direct access to their information."
Others say that the site could provide a means of identifying and addressing health and social problems.
According to a recent study by Mr. Megan Moreno of Wisconsin University, and his colleagues, young students who spoke on Facebook about their drunken exploits had a lot more chance of being alcoholic than those who were discreet about it.
Megan Moreno suggested that students' colleagues, such as counsellors, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student whose status would be too often about alcohol.
"You can't deal with a problem if you don't diagnose it," said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Megan Moreno and director of the Centre for Children's Health, Behaviour and Development at the Research Institute for Children in Seattle, Washington Post.
"We know how to identify children at risk, and who would not otherwise be recognized."
Facebook also has constant access to the information of its users.
The data team studied statistics on the situation of Valentine's Day, the participation rate in the 2010 mid-term elections and a national rate of happiness (only available information - digital freedom champions have for a long time argued that the site could make its data treasure available to others for research purposes).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - in return for being able to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, the site is allowed to access your information.
But what happens when Facebook users are part of an investigation they haven't even heard of?
While researchers have well-defined instructions on how to collect information other than through the Internet, it is something else online.
"I don't think a lot of users have ever thought about the fact that a researcher could study their profile," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, according to a 2006 study that he conducted by observing the Facebook walls of his students.
"As far as they know, the exchanges were seen only by their friends."
Then comes the question of methodology.
Even without going through the Internet, there is no guarantee that the subject of a study is completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know the degree of truth of a profile or on a user's wall.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do in reality are two completely different things," says Neil Selwyn.
