Replacing analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has suffered in recent years
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) has emerged from the constitutional controversy that the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have formulated against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analogue cupupre" from 2021 to 2015, because the eight votes required to invalidate it have not been gathered.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers when he issued the decree detailing the actions to be taken to implement the transition to terrestrial digital television.
With this result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic has been set aside for failing to reach the qualified majority of eight votes so that the Court can decide on the constitutional or non-constitutional nature of the decree, and this continues to be in force.
The draft award, prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed the decree's declaration as non-constitutional, because radio and television regulations are a statutory award to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Coffel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and statutory reservation.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted in favour of the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies promoted two constitutional controversies to challenge the decree and to admit the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions envisaged by it for the digital transition.
The plenary meeting of Ministers also resolved to resolve the complaint made by the Chamber of Deputies, without discussing the project of which Minister Sánchez Cordero is also responsible.
In his speech, the President said that he disagreed with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the Federal Executive cannot structure through general standards the measures to be prepared for the public administration to do so.
"I also consider that if it is being done, it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," he recalled that planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the Federal Executive, which has the constitutional mandate of the government.
Substituting analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has suffered in recent years and this results in better exploitation of the radio spectrum, better quality of the signal and more channels.
To adjourn the change, he supported, would be to adjourn the benefits of digitisation which implies a decision of public interest which not only has a technical dimension, "because it also includes economic, social, political and national security issues".
These questions, he stressed, "are requiring the operation of a whole system to establish, in accordance with the principle of economic direction of the State, a group of powers which the Constitution grants to the Executive of the State".
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the digital transition and they have done so through the Executive, despite their having the highly specialized technical organs.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, by issuing the contested decree, has in one form invaded the sphere of competence of the Congress, as it ensures in the administrative sphere that the laws issued by the legislature are respected.
