MSS announces protocol to find the gene of obesity
Social Insurance conducts an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in the case of children and young people; this is supported by NPI specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Assurance (IMSS) has announced that it conducts an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in the case of children and young people, called the protocol 'Genetics of obesity of children and adolescents' that will allow to have markers associated with overweight.
In a press release, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Specialities Hospital of the National Medical Centre of the 20th Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of physicians, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been trained.
This team is supported by third-cycle specialists and students of the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Advanced Research and Studies (Cinvesav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (INP).
In the investigation, it is invited to participate the population with or without the right to attend the participating sports units of the IMSS in Valle de México, where evidence is given to minors every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the sports unit Cuauhtémoc (State of Mexico West) and that as of 8 October, the activity takes place in the sports unit of Nezahualcoyolt (State of Mexico East).
After reaching the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue in the Sports Independence Unit (south of Federal District) and finally in the Sportive Morelos Unit (north of Federal District).
He explained that the objective of this investigation and that is to know the components and the importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify in Mexican children and young people risk factors to prevent chronic degenerative diseases.
As will be celebrated on 14 November on World Diabetes Day, he noted that the goal is to bring together three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14 years, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the application of specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and history of family legacy of their diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that Saturdays will be applied to all participants in anthropometric measurements (weight, size, size, circumference of size), arterial pressure, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic levels (i.e., people associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López reported that this investigation is the result of the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys reported that, in just six years, there was an increase of 77 per cent in obesity and 47 per cent in overweight girls, and there was also a dramatic increase in overweight girls,' said the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country is different from the others by its genetic history.
He informed that, on average, Mexicans have 65 per cent of indo-American inheritance, 30 per cent European and 5 per cent African, and that condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, obesity genetics translate into the inability to burn the excess of energy consumed (calories), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the full evaluation of children, which allows them to detect if they present a degree of overweight or obesity.
She even said that the presence of dark-colored plus (acanthosis) on the neck and forearms indicate the probability of suffering from metabolic and even pre-diabetes alterations.
The information is managed in a confidential manner, and the doctors write it to the parents, to whom each is explained of the measures and changes in the lifestyle they must carry out in order to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentaryism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, stay most of the day sitting in front of the TV and use means of transport instead of walking on short distances.
Another cause is high calorie intake, i.e. the largest consumption of sugar drinks, carbohydrates (palms - meat pasta to corn flour wrapped in corn leaves -, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM's asphalt would avoid the cassation
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemicals of UNAM, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better yield, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signs were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair approximately 200 thousand cassia every rain season in the Metropolitan Zone of the Valley of Mexico, alert Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who ensured that if the process of construction and maintenance of the bituminous paving is adequate, the casssia could be reduced or even eliminated completely.
During his conference A technological opinion on the cassis, organized within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory he is responsible develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of the asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve the yield, and therefore, the formation of cassis.
He explained that the asphalt, the heavier part of the oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called malthenes, which together give the paved its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behaviour of the asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures, almost 180 degrees, behaves like a liquid, 120 degrees C its viscosity is very large and at 50 degrees C it presents an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, adds.
This means that in the streets the resistance of asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, warns the specialist in chemical engineering.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City in most of them were covered by a flexible pavement, consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the more superficial layers is the layer of asphalt, consisting of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the small stones that forms the layer, pointed out, is bathed an asphalt.
When vehicles pass through the vehicle by generating efforts, it allows forces to propagate very well into the pavement.
If the asphalt was altered, the asphalt would propagate better, the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt layer, he says, we put a last layer called rolling layer, made of fine stone, that is, sand which is also bathed in asphalt.
Since this is the layer in contact with the wheels of vehicles, it must have more mechanical force than the asphalt layer and provide adhesion in the street.
Being the part of the Pave that receives and distributes the efforts, the rolling layer also requires that the Pave requires adequate thickness and the material it is made to be treated.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, is also a very important factor to consider, especially water, as they significantly affect the yield of the asphalt layer.
When the soil is wet, the water spreads inside the layer, it is difficult to do so, which swirls all the layers of the pavement and therefore causes the cassation.
In the process of forming a cassation, he said, the first one that gets damaged is the rolling film and only later the asphalt layer is affected, but the damage is not done immediately, but it is a process that needs to be treated for the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National Searcher System explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor for the formation of cassation and therefore the thickness of each layer of the pavement must always be linked to the load of vehicles and ensure its satisfaction, in order to avoid frequent training of cassation.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and allow for easy repair of casses and without having to use high temperatures.
