Thus it was the work of the person of Cali who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A Cali dactyloscopicist went to history like the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano'.
The work of these officials is crucial.
Last November 4th, a CTI miner from Cali came to history as the person who confirmed the identity of the supreme chief of the Farcs: "Alfonso Cano", confronting his fingerprints.
Seven Dactyloscopicists working at the local ITC offices, this week was the "availability' tour of Eliasar González, a man of Puerto Tejada who has been working in the field of judicial investigation for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in the municipalities of Chocó, where many times he had to spend more than five days in the forest to get to the place where the bodies were to be identified.
In the year 2000, he moved to the capital of Valle and after following proper courses, he specialized in dactyloscopic, which is the study of friction skin, i.e. palms and feet.
During the week of the operation against alias Alfonso Cano we warned Eliasar to take with him clothes for at least three days.
Something very big was waiting for him.
On Friday night he left for Cauca in a Palmira helicopter.
He knew that he had to identify two bodies and that one of them was suspected to be the man who was leading the oldest guerrilla in the world, so he was asked to take the card with the ten fingerprints of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
But when he arrived with the investigation team at the place of the body, he did not recognize it by its physical appearance, because it was very different from the one he had seen in the media.
He had no beard, he was dressed like a peasant in the area, without glasses and much lighter.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Accompanied by a galton wolf, ink, a picker and a lantern, Eliasar compared the fingerprints of the corpse to those of the map.
His eye did not wrong him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was responsible who confirmed to the Minister of Defence Juan Carlos Pinzón that yes, he was the supreme leader of the Farcs.
Looking for the print
For a Dactyloscopicist of Sijín de Cali the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos made to Eliasar González, in a press conference for the operation against "Cano", is very significant.
A lot of people don't know about our work.
Dactyloscopic is an accurate science, without margin of error, which can be crucial in the resolution of crimes.
Apart from identifying the bodies, dictators support investigations into crimes such as theft and homicide and confirm the identity of those captured.
When captured, many offenders have false identity cards or do not have any documents.
We take their fingerprints and searches in the database.
The researcher said that in a flight case he had to remove a piece of wall from a house, because in that place the thief had held his hand to get out a safe full of jewels and silver.
"The walls are difficult because they are not adequate surfaces to draw a digital print, but in this case we were able to get the fingerprint of all our hands and identify the offender who had participated in different flights," he recalls.
Prints may also rule out or confirm suspects in cases of homicide.
Recently we found a dead man, with bottles of drinking around him.
Through the investigation, it was determined that a parent may be suspected of the crime and indeed a fingerprint on the bottle coincided.
Even though it doesn't guarantee he's the killer, it puts him on the crime scene.
One ITC dictator explained that "the fingerprints of objects with chemical or physical reagents" are extracted.
When they appear, a picker or a band is used to remove them.
Subsequently, fingerprints are sent to Asif, the declicant database, or to the National Civil Registry.
"The problem is that there are still many undocumented Colombians," said the ITC expert.
He explained that everything is not how we show in the CSI television program.
As everything that shines is not gold, all that you touch does not necessarily become a fingerprint.
It can, however, be used if the necessary confrontation is made.
