The North Stream, a new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The North Stream gas pipeline, connecting Western Europe directly to Russia by going to the bottom of the Baltic Sea, went into service.
It must provide gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with bursts.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, participated, on Tuesday, on the shores of the Baltic, between orchestra and fine buffets, at the inauguration of the North Stream, this new gas pipeline which connects Russia directly, under the sea, to Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his counterpart from the Netherlands Mark Rutte turned together the wheel of the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new gas pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic metres of Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe by a 1 224 km first tube connecting the St. Petersburg region to the Land of Mecklemburg-Pomerania.
A second tube has to be completed at the end of 2012, allowing a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, equivalent to all French consumption.
And we already mention the possibility of building a third on the same route.
For Gazprom, the completion in time and time of this huge construction site has airs of victory.
The project had been strongly challenged by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The North Stream will enable gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding any land crossing through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries lose some of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close access to the West European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the North Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is whether the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security from its supplies.
But it is at the price of a weakening of Europe of energy, since the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has been able to triumph over its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which are heavily gas consumers, and whose deposits are declining.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that links us organically," confirmed François Fillon by opening this gas pipeline, demonstrating to what extent the major gas contracts are both political and economic.
All of this explains the broad smiles displayed by the Gazprom leaders, present in numbers in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also a technical operation.
The submarine tube is made of concrete-gained steel to protect it against ships' anchors.
It rests on the seabed, at an average of 200 m.
In order to build it, it was necessary to avoid mines from the Second World War.
" A hundred must have been removed or destroyed by caution," said Jens Müller, spokesperson for North Stream.
There was also a need to multiply the measures to protect wildlife and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, which nothing interrupts on its entire length: neither valve nor maintenance station.
A control platform was planned off Sweden, but project managers gave up while the Swedish were reluctant to see a Russian state society permanently on their shores.
"In case of damage, we stop the gas in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas in the gas pipeline escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who have planned the welds to experience a leak every 100,000 years.
The monitoring of the state of the pipeline is carried out by a underwater robot, driven by a vessel, for external observation, and by a device that circulates inside the pipeline.
Of the form of a cigar, it is introduced inside the tube, wide by a diameter, and it is pushed by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at the 3 metre second speed, he provides accurate information on possible metal deformations.
The gas pipeline was designed to run for 50 years without having to suffer any repair.
Gas circulation is simply driven by pressure.
It is 200 bar at the start, and 100 bar at the finish.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which keeps 51% of the shares.
Germany joined E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French GDF Suez group (9% each).
These five companies have established a joint venture, called Nord Stream, which is responsible for building and operating the gas pipeline.
It has its seat in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the total gas transport capacity to this company for twenty renewable years.
" Gazprom will pay for total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported," says Jens Müller.
Funding for the construction of the pipeline was provided to 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work is expected to be EUR 7.4 billion for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment has increased to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to return to their fees, as only Gazprom takes the risk.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic to Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted with pines.
Valves, 4.5 meters tall, form the gas outlet door.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the gas that comes before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since Tuesday, this terminal receives a million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour that passes.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
